# Module 10: Untangling Users

## Becoming root with su
Every shell command, including every program and every builtin, exits with an exit code when it finishes running and terminates. This can be used by the shell, or the user of the shell (that's you!) to check if the process succeeded in its functionality (this determination, of course, depends on what the process is supposed to do in the first place).

It's not just hackers that need to become root. Oftentimes, you, as the owner of your computer, need to use root access to administer it. Becoming root is a fairly common action that Linux users take, and there are two utilities that exist for this purpose: su and sudo.

In this challenge, we will cover the older one, su (the substitute user command). This is not typically used to elevate to root access anymore, but it is an elegant utility from a more civilized time, and we'll cover it first.

su is a setuid binary:

hacker@dojo:~$ ls -l /usr/bin/su
-rwsr-xr-x 1 root root 232416 Dec 1 11:45 /usr/bin/su
hacker@dojo:~$
Because it has the SUID bit set, su runs as root. Running as root, it can start a root shell! Of course, su is discerning: before allowing the user to elevate privileges to root, it checks to make sure that the user knows the root password:

hacker@dojo:~$ su
Password: 
su: Authentication failure
hacker@dojo:~$
This check against the root password is what obsoletes su. Modern systems very rarely have root passwords, and different mechanisms (that we will learn later) are used to grant administrative access.

But THIS challenge (and only this challenge) does have a root password. That password is hack-the-planet, and you must provide it to su to become root! Go do that, and read the flag!


### Solve
**Flag:** `pwn.college{4fFddyAEHwSnCmpVj2bOh5jlwfA.QX2UDN1wiNyUDN0EzW}`

The challenge required elevating privileges using the su command, which runs with root permissions because it is a setuid binary. Authentication was enforced through a root password, and successful verification granted a root shell. Once elevated, restricted system resources became accessible, allowing retrieval of the flag.

```bash
hacker@users~other-users-with-su:~$ su zardus
Password: 
zardus@users~other-users-with-su:/home/hacker$ /challenge/run
Congratulations, you have become Zardus! Here is your flag:
pwn.college{4fFddyAEHwSnCmpVj2bOh5jlwfA.QX2UDN1wiNyUDN0EzW}
```

### New Learnings
Learned that setuid programs execute with the file owner’s privileges, enabling controlled privilege escalation. Learned that su verifies the root password before granting administrative access. Learned that root privileges override normal user restrictions, highlighting the importance of proper authentication mechanisms.